ce:section.ce:para:
However, there is currently confusion about the role of MXenes in photoinduced carrier separation. Specifically, the surface chemistry of MXene subsequently affected the work function (Φ) [36,37], which is the crucial factor on its role in the photocatalytic reaction [38]. On the one hand, some studies confirmed that -O adsorbed MXene (Ti3C2
                     Ox
                     ) with high work function (low Fermi level) plays the role of electron cocatalyst [39,40]. On the other hand, the –OH terminated MXene has a completely different effect in photocatalytic reactions, which has been demonstrated it has ultralow work function [41,42], and acts as a hole mediator [41–48]. Obviously, the surface chemistry of MXene is closely related to synthesize routes [49] and post-processing methods [50]. Until now, the most common preparation method of MXene is the HF etching pioneering developed by Naguib et al. [51], meanwhile, mixture of fluoride salt and acid instead of HF was exploited [52]. Subsequently, hydrothermal [53], water-free route [54], and fluorine-free route including high-temperature alkali treatment [55], electrochemical etching [56], and molten-salt etching approach [57] were both exploited for the synthesis of MXenes. Furthermore, it is vital to investigate its surface group composition and work functions (Φ) according to its specific preparation conditions to clarify its role in photocatalytic reactions.
